text:
A potential bridge between Cardano ($ADA) and Polkadot ($DOT) is sparking community interest...

A New Bridge Under Discussion :

The Polkadot community is exploring the potential for a bridge between the #Polkadot and #Cardano networks. Discussions are underway regarding the feasibility of this project. According to Unifires ecosystem agent Felix, a Cardano-Polkadot light client and NFT exchange bridge are currently under development, and the proposal has already been submitted to Cardano for review. A similar proposal will soon be presented to OpenGov, Polkadot's decentralized governance body...

Proposal and Potential Impact :

Felix shared on the #Polkadot forum that the proposal, if approved, could significantly benefit both ecosystems. The main objective is to obtain funding for a project that will solve the interoperability problems prevalent in the cryptocurrency sector. Blockchain bridges are crucial to solving these challenges, and this initiative could provide substantial benefits to both #Polkadot and #Cardano.

Since their inception, #Polkadot and #Cardano, created by Ethereum co-founders @gavofyork and @IOHK_Charles, have made significant technical progress and seen their number of users increase. This new interoperability effort is expected to further strengthen the utility of both blockchains, particularly with upcoming major upgrades intended to transform their ecosystems...

Community Reaction :

Initial community reaction to the proposal has been largely positive. Polkadot Chief Ambassador Tommi Enenkel, also known as Alice and Bob, commented on the feasibility of building the bridge. 

In advising on how the bridge could be built, Enenkel advocated the most direct method, saying : 

‚ÄúFor the Polkadot>Cardano management, I think the simplest approach would be to check the Beefy proofs on a contract on Cardano L1...‚Äù

#Cardano fam, just wanted to add some additional clarity for some y‚Äôall with respect to ‚Äúliquidity‚Äù & @wmtoken.

The term liquidity is often overused and misunderstood in general when talking about crypto.

Specifically in terms of $WMTX, the token supply remains unchanged. Going cross chain is an amazing development! 

Why?

Because that BRINGS liquidity to the token as it gains ACCESS to other markets & participants.

How does this help the CNT? 

Because of ARBITRAGE.

Arbitrage is the simultaneous purchase and sale of an asset in different markets to exploit tiny differences in their prices. Arbitrage trades are made in stocks, commodities, and currencies. Arbitrage takes advantage of the inevitable inefficiencies in markets.

So for that reason if $WMTX is more expensive on @base what do you imagine traders are going to do?

They will BUY more of the cheaper WMTX on @Cardano and sell it on Base. This will in actual fact increase trading volume on our Dex‚Äôs!!

This is a bullish event. Congrats @MrTelecoms & team.

text:
#Cardano has successfully overcome DDoS and some influencers and media are annoyed.

To clarify a few points:

‚û°Ô∏è Any blockchain can be targeted with a DDoS attack if the attacker is prepared to invest the necessary funds.
‚û°Ô∏è Such attacks are typically carried out by an individual or a small group.
‚û°Ô∏è The objective of a DDoS attack is to saturate the network‚Äôs resources, preventing regular users from accessing services.
‚û°Ô∏è In severe cases, nodes (servers) may crash, rendering the service completely inoperative.
‚û°Ô∏è During a DDoS attack, funds remain secure as they are safeguarded by private keys.

How did Cardano overcome a DDoS attack? Successfully!

Despite the increased load from validating numerous spam transactions, most services on Cardano remained operational during the DDoS attack.

The network operated continuously without the need for a reboot. 

Throughout the attack, Cardano managed to process 1.8 million transactions, maintaining an approximate rate of 40 TPS.

The community identified a method to retrieve $ADA from the attacker.

The development team quickly issued a hotfix. SPOs are advised to upgrade to the new node version 8.12.1.

While there are networks boasting higher TPS, they too are vulnerable to DDoS attacks. Some require a system reboot following such incidents, with teams spending weeks devising a hotfix.

Some networks have addressed DDoS attacks through centralization measures, such as designating specific block producers or imposing substantial deposits that can be confiscated by the team/network.

text:
Coindesk reported a DDoS attack on #Cardano. Let me clarify one important thing.

It is not possible to attack staked $ADA through a DDoS attack.

ADAs are protected by private keys held by the owners. 

ADAs are in users' wallets during staking.

ADA coins are delegated to pools through certificates. These certificates are stored in the blockchain. 

A pool can mint blocks on behalf of ADA owners, but the pool operator does not control the coins.

Only private key holders can spend ADA from their wallet by signing a transaction.

If a hacker wanted to attack staked ADA, he would have to attack users, not the pool or the network.

If stakers use HW wallets, then good luck to hackers.

text:
#Cardano recently faced a DDoS attack, but the network performed as anticipated, merely experiencing a slowdown. 

Most services, including SundaeSwap, which processed 5013 orders, operated effectively during the attack. 

The attacker incurred transaction fees, ultimately losing money without causing significant disruption.

Cardano is the winner because its resilience has been proven.

Come see how complicated it is to commit a DDoS attack on Cardano.

The intent behind a DDoS attack on a blockchain is to hinder user access by overwhelming the network with spam transactions. 

These transactions are valid but costly due to the fees the attacker must pay.

Invalid transactions would not be diffused.

In contrast to client-server networks where attacks are directed at one or a few servers, Cardano's distributed structure comprises numerous nodes, each with its own mem-pool, making such attacks more complex. 

An attacker would need to simultaneously target hundreds of nodes.

Each block-producing node in Cardano maintains a mem-pool, a kind of waiting room for transactions before they are included in a block. 

By default, the mem-pool is sized to hold double the number of transactions of the current block size, which equates to roughly 600 standard transactions.

Transactions are processed on a first-come, first-served basis. 

A newly submitted transaction is passed from the relay node to the block-producer node, where it is stored in the mem-pool and then diffused to other block-producing nodes.

Cardano operates on a demand-driven protocol, allowing each node to manage its data rate, concurrency, and data volume. 

Nodes request additional work only when they are ready to process it. The work is not pushed on them.

The Node-to-Node (NtN) protocol manages transaction transfers between full nodes through relay nodes. It includes three mini-protocols: chain-sync, block-fetch, and tx-submission. 

These are multiplexed over a single TCP channel. 

NtN uses a pull-based strategy, where the initiator node requests new transactions, and the responder node supplies them if available. 

This protocol is well-suited for a trustless environment, protecting both parties from resource consumption attacks.

Figure 1 demonstrates block diffusion among pools via mini-protocols. 

Alice sends a transaction to Node 1, marked by red arrows. Node 2, with space in its mem-pool, requests transactions from nearby nodes. It receives Alice's transaction from Node 1, illustrated by blue arrows 1 to 6. Later, Node 3 does the same with Node 2, shown by blue arrows 7 to 12, ensuring Alice's transaction is in all mem-pools.

Nodes are responsible for validating transactions before relaying them. 

Invalid or unsolicited transactions can lead to disconnection. 

Mem-pools are concurrently populated from different network locations, with transactions disseminated through mini-protocols as needed.

Figure 2 shows the sequential filling of three mem-pools. 

Alice, Bob, and Bot submit transactions from various places. Initially, each mem-pool holds one transaction. As time progresses, nodes pull transactions from peers, resulting in mem-pools containing both user and spam transactions.

No matter which node becomes the slot leader, the transaction included in the next block will be the same, emptying all mem-pools.

A bot could flood a node with spam transactions, filling its mem-pool and preventing further transaction acceptance. 

However, this doesn't stop other nodes from processing user transactions.

Don't forget that slot leaders are randomly drawn based on the stakes of pools.

The likelihood of a successful attack grows with the number of targeted nodes, as more mem-pools would be filled with spam. Yet, this also increases the attack's complexity and cost.

Figure 3 shows a bot sending spam transactions to Node 1, while Alice and Bob send valid transactions to Node 3. If Node 3 becomes the slot leader, the block will mainly contain user transactions.

When a new block arrives, nodes remove the included transactions from their mem-pools, freeing up space for new ones.

If all mem-pools contained 600 identical spam transactions, they would be cleared within two blocks (40 seconds). 

If the spam transactions were unique, only one mem-pool would be cleared in the same timeframe.

An attacker aiming to damage the network must submit unique transactions and incur fees. 

Flooding all 3000 mem-pools with unique transactions would require 1.8 million transactions, costing approximately 300,000 $ADA.

The network could process this volume of transactions in about 33 hours (6,000 blocks). 

High throughput is a deterrent against spam attacks, as it requires more transactions to be submitted, raising the cost of the attack.

For instance, if the Ouroboros Leios protocol increased Cardano's throughput by 100 times, the network could handle the same volume of spam transactions in just 30 minutes.

text:
We've delivered Cardano the Bitcoin bridge, we need your assistance to deliver Runes!

Rosen Bridge is an open source technology that creates a direct and secure connection between the #Bitcoin and #Cardano blockchains. This connection is particularly designed to allow the integration of Bitcoin Runes with Cardano.

Here's what it does:
üî∏It allows Bitcoin Runes to be "wrapped" and transferred onto the Cardano blockchain. Think of "wrapping" as packaging Bitcoin Runes in a way that they can be recognized and used on the Cardano system.

üî∏Once wrapped, these Bitcoin Runes can tap into Cardano's sophisticated decentralized finance (DeFi) features. This means that Bitcoin and Bitcoin Rune holders can now access financial services on Cardano that were previously unavailable to them.

üî∏The Rosen Bridge ensures that this integration is smooth and secure, so Bitcoin Rune holders can easily join and use Cardano's DeFi applications.

The goal is to bring users from the Bitcoin ecosystem into Cardano's DeFi space, expanding the reach and utility of both cryptocurrencies.

‚ÑπÔ∏è For more details, you can visit the Cardano IdeaScale page üëá

https://t.co/MqadU9PafS

#Cardano fam, see some y‚Äôall asking what this vote is for and what is the Interim Constitutional Committee (ICC)?

The launch of Voltaire commences with the creation of the ICC. To kickstart/transition governance the voted in members will be coded into the Conway Genesis file during the Chang Hardfork.

The 3 founding entities (@InputOutputHK, @emurgo_io, @Cardano_CF) are represented with a seat as is @IntersectMBO. @Cardano community is choosing three (3) members to join the ICC. The Constitutional Committee has significant power in the ecosystem. Governance Actions are implemented with a required 5/7 members vote.

text:
Tomorrow is a big day for #Cardano.

You can vote for 3 new members of the ‚ÄúInterim‚Äù Constitution Committee (CC).

Voting will only last 10 days. Voting ends on June 23.

22 candidates are registered.

A few important details and links.

The CC will initially consist of 7 members.

4 of these will be appointed from established entities: IOG, Cardano Foundation, Emurgo, and Intersect MBO.

ADA holders will vote on 3 committee members in the next 10 days.

3 new Interim CC members will be announced on June 26.

The interim period concludes with the on-chain ratification of the final version of the Constitution, anticipated to follow the Constitutional Convention in Argentina, in December 2024.

The Interim CC's role includes enabling the initial phase of the Chang hard fork.

Every $ADA holder had the opportunity to self-nominate for committee membership, resulting in a diverse, candidate pool comprising individuals and consortia.

On the list you will find quality candidates and one "well-known" troll.

There are also several consortia.

The inclusive process required no preliminary filtering or criteria, though candidates had to respond to several simple questions.

Based on the answers, it is very easy to recognize candidates and consortia that deserve attention.

Check out the candidates and their answers:
https://t.co/1z94aHLR1i

Voting will be conducted via the Summon Platform accessible through a Cardano wallet:
https://t.co/bMiojzupGW

All ADA holders are eligible to vote, with voting power proportional to their ADA stake.

The ranked-choice voting system enables voters to prioritize their top 3 candidates and select three alternates.

The limited time for candidate promotion and the absence of moderated debates may affect the quality of candidate visibility.

Well-known figures in the Cardano ecosystem have a chance to be elected. New faces may have a worse position.

Nonetheless, a subsequent election within a year will necessitate incumbents to justify their positions, while new aspirants must articulate their vision for Cardano.

You can debate the candidates in the post and use it for promotion.

Good luck!

text:
The @Cardano blockchain is set to enter the final phase of its decentralization process 

@IOHK_Charles said this will happen after the next hard fork that will introduce the Voltaire era. Currently, in the Basho era, #Cardano will transition to being managed entirely by its community, marking a big shift from its current management by IOHK. The Voltaire era will bring new governance structures, with annual budgets, a treasury, and a framework for community guidance.
One of the key features of Voltaire is the empowerment of ADA holders, who will be able to vote on important network topics. This approach aims to ensure that the community has a direct say in the future direction of Cardano. 
 https://t.co/EEkmI7X1z5

quote.text:
I‚Äôm an Ethereum node validator mining for over 1100 days! Why because I saw the connections with TradFi years ago and so I took a bet on ETH and wanted to support what they called ETH2.

But over the years, I‚Äôve been seeing things which I disagree with. LSD‚Äôs, restaking, and sadly this extreme bias with ENS.

These conflicts of interest are fuelled solely by their investments and the price of tokens! It‚Äôs an attempt for an inner circle to hold a monopoly over certain services.

The @ethereum foundation recently suggested they need to work on these financial conflicts of interest. The problem is, imho they are empty words. 

I‚Äôm not sure they can actually put their biases aside because they‚Äôre so deeply intertwined with these tokens financially they are ethically and morally corrupt.

They can‚Äôt deny it because they are literally saying these things publicly, we have the receipts recorded in podcasts hosted on the Internet for everyone to hear and see. 

And for this reason I believe in a multi chain paradigm. Because if you‚Äôre going to sit on a high horse with such arrogance believing that nothing can compete due to a first mover advantage.

To me that is a sign of lackadaisical leadership with their eyes off the ball, bellies already too fat from feeding off the ERC-20 trough for too long.

@IOHK_Charles has made a loud and clear message to @BanklessHQ that if they wish to mock their research and technology at least have the balls to go and do it in person to their communities faces, instead of hiding behind a computer screen with the Ethereum army backing them up.

Charles is right, I‚Äôve not seen Ethereum Maxis talk about any other protocol in the many years I‚Äôve been around in a positive manner. Unless it‚Äôs an L2 of course!

They throw shade on anything they‚Äôre not connected to financially and for some reason the same goes for .eth they disingenuously push a narrative that it‚Äôs the only Ethereum name service üòÇ and ironically after doing exactly the same to the Solana community @BanklessHQ have bizarrely pivoted and have been banging on about Solana for about a year now since it hit it‚Äôs low of $7 üëÄ and Vitalik jumped in to pump it! ‚òùÔ∏è

I would bet my bottom dollar these guys are heavily invested in Solana now, possible fraudulent and misleading behaviour from social networking influencers pumping their bags. No one would be surprised, this is crypto after all.

@VitalikButerin knows that if he ever murmured the words of another TLD that uses the Ethereum blockchain that it would harm the price of the ENS token. And that‚Äôs why he will pretend for as long as possible that ENS is the only decentralised DNS protocol on the Ethereum Blockchain ü§¶‚Äç‚ôÇÔ∏è

ENS is not even decentralised because of the way they use token weighted governance and the major holders of the tokens happen to be Binance, Coinbase a16z et al and other whales that we‚Äôre not too sure who they actually are?

And for that reason last night I decided I‚Äôll buy a bit of Cardano and start rooting for them a bit more, because I think their academic approach is a wise move and it‚Äôs quite possible in the end that the shade thrown at the Cardano community will backfire and be looked back on as childish, foolish, and financially conflicted tribalism that wanted to hold back technology not for the greater good of humanity, but for financial gains.

So that‚Äôs my weekend rant, sorry but I don‚Äôt brown nose. You‚Äôll learn that about me over time. 

Intellectual honesty is the best way for us to move decentralised technologies forward. Don‚Äôt screw up something amazing because you guys are more focused on the money than decentralisation because that‚Äôs not what the Cypherpunk values are meant to uphold! 

Am I fudding my own bags? Yes! Because it‚Äôs the right thing to do to push for decentralised progression.

#Cardano #ETH #BTC

Never in my career have I seen such a profound disconnect between reality and opinion with the cryptocurrency influencer and media perception of Cardano versus its actual fundamentals. 

We are on the verge of the most significant hard fork in the history of the project, tons of community DApps are growing rapidly, we are leading the industry in scaling R&D, rare evo is going to be a huge event, the Foundation summit huge, we'll be at Token 2049, technologies like Hydra are maturing, we have partnerchains, midnight, prism, tons of community events, catalyst, and then the constitutional convention in Argentina. 

It's becoming impossible to keep up with, and it has much good news coming in just the next six months. Then I look at the cryptomedia, and the headlines are "Will Cardano die?"

It's beyond pathetic and just reflects on the low quality and low effort they put into our ecosystem.  Cardano is here to stay, and it's a juggernaut that will drag this industry kicking and screaming if it has to towards solving the real-world economic, political, and social issues we all face.

text:
Cardano is a very strong Ecosystem. 

However, I believe what hurts #Cardano the most isn't IOG, The CF, or Emurgo. What hurts Cardano the most is it's Community. 

We have a segment of our Community who will give anyone & everyone (including self-acclaimed saviors) who says anything positive about #Cardano, their money, time, support, likes, views, organs, firstborn, life.. ok, ok, you get the point. And the ppl these folks empower are usually the greediest ones that want every penny, lovelace, dollar, $ADA,  pool, delegator, early memecoin access, ounce of fame, NFT collection, etc.. And EVEN when they have that, they still want treasury funding & unwavering Community support. 

And Another side of the Community that believes in Decentralization, Equality, power to the edges, we'll all win together, work hard, stay humble, never flock, help each other, Support the Real, we're a decentralized team, lets effin GO, Cardano, Change the World!! etc.

But greed from a few can kill a Whole Paradise.. Ami right?

This is how a beautiful Community can become toxic. It's because some of the richest influencers are constantly getting wealthy off of the Community believing their false promises while they deliver nothing of scale, quality, longevity, or real significance. I think they are absolute Cancers to the Community & have been every step of the Incentivized Era. 

'Our Blockchain has never faultered, and yet our Community can never Equate.'

I believe this is why we have lost some battles in the Space. To live Cardano's ultimate purpose, the funding & support should go to ALL SPOs, Legitimate Builders,  World Changers, & Community Organizers.. not to the 6th & 7th pools of Greedy influencers who apparently will NEVER stop at any cost, even as they watch their 'friends' retire. The ecosystem needs to grow for all, not for the few.

Decentraliztion IS the whole point of Blockchain. So that power cannot become concentrated.

So, Respect to the Real Builders & Long-Term Cardano Projects that are in the trenches for the right reasons (To Enhance a Thriving Community). These are the folks I want to see on YouTube Weekly/Monthly. The Aiken Devs, The Vespr Team, @berry_ales, eternl, Blockfrost Team, CardanoGirl SPOs & Builders, Taptools Team, https://t.co/l4wxZfwBuE, Duncan, Aggelos, The DexHunters üê≤, World Mobile, Iagon, Axo Squad, @CornucopiasGame, etc.. 

#StrongerTogether

#Cardano in the past 4 years has changed dramatically.

We have gone from a wallet with delegated staking to a fully functional ecosystem of businesses built on the layer 1.

Cardano is the second longest running blockchain behind Bitcoin.

Cardano has never been hacked, has had no outages, no failed TXs
